his passport says he is a citizen of germany he 
speaks its language with perfect fluency and has a law degree from 
one of its finest universities his wife and two children are 
german 
but one day vu dinh nimh went to an unemployment agency to see 
about a job he said the man at the reception desk directed him to 
a special section for foreigners 
second floor the man said 
but im german vu told the man 
youre not german the man said you dont even belong 
here why dont you go back where you came from 
so vu went back to where he came from back to his sootcovered 
tenement back to his a rundown neighborhood back to his family in 
their cramped apartment in the capital of the new germany 
vu is a vietnamese native who came here in 1974 to study at east 
berlins prestigious humboldt university and fell in love with a 
german woman who worked in the math department 
hes also one of thousands of foreignborn residents who believe 
they are being shut out of the former nations job market as it 
struggles to adapt to a free market 
about 95000 vietnamese mozambicans and cubans worked in the 
country under contracts made with their countries by the old 
communist government of what was east germany 
gabriela endertreinhart a spokeswoman for the employment 
office in berlin said there were no statistics on how many of them 
are still working but most have left the country and many of those 
remaining are jobless 
its germanys shame that people we invited here to work are 
being unfairly fired she said 
most the the guest workers about 60000 are vietnamese about 
3800 of the 4600 in eastern berlin have lost their jobs said 
tran manh tuan vietnamese diplomatic attache in berlin 
foreigners have become victims of violent attacks and increasing 
hostility in eastern germany a situation blamed in large part on 
the dire economic situation 
vu had to go back to vietnam when he completed his education in 
1979 but came back three years later as a guest worker in a 
factory he married his college sweetheart jutta kerger and the 
couple built a life 
he eventually got a decent job as a translator for 200 
vietnamese workers at the gold point shoe factory in berlin in 
august however those workers were let go 
vu said he has had no success finding work and doesnt expect 
to the family has applied for permission to immigrate to canada 
the couple and their two children 3yearold martin and emily 
6 live in the drab lichtenberg district of berlin 
recently vu said he took emily to her school and a group of 
high school students nearby shouted racial and antiforeigner 
epithets 
they said today well let you live but next time well kill 
you recalled vu 37 
another time he took martin to a grocery store to buy bread a 
group of neonazi skinheads loitering outside refused to let them 
enter 
there never used to be problems before the economic situation 
got worse vu says i could say good day to people on the 
street and they would say good day back 
in the familys neat clean tiny tworoom apartment the door 
has a sticker a red maple leaf the symbol of canada they think 
of canada as a land tolerant of foreigners and mixed marriages a 
place with no barriers to employment for smart competent people 
they live three doors down from the house where jutta lived as a 
child a neighborhood where they could once stroll together 
now they cant wait to leave 
