arsenicpoisoning death of her boyfriend administered repeated 
doses of the poison to her two husbands one of whom died a 
prosecutor charged monday 
in closing arguments the defense said the state had failed to 
prove that blanche taylor moore killed her boyfriend raymond reid 
mrs moore 57 is on trial for firstdegree murder in the death 
of raymond reid 
she also is charged in the death of her first husband james 
taylor in 1973 and with two counts of assault in the near lethal 
arsenic poisoning last year of her nowestranged husband the rev 
dwight moore she will be tried on those charges later 
prosecutors used those poisonings in the fourweek trial in an 
effort to establish a pattern that pointed to mrs moore 
when you combine all the evidence what hits you directly in 
the face forsyth county district attorney warren sparrow asked the 
jury 
there was arsenic in mr taylor repeatedly administered 
sparrow said what about dwight moore the same thing the 
fundamental picture is repeated doses of arsenic 
this is not circumstantial this is direct and powerful 
scientific evidence that points unerringly at the defendant he 
said 
prosecutors have said they will ask for the death penalty if 
mrs moore is convicted 
defense attorney david tamer said the states case was nothing 
more than circumstantial saying that at no point did any witness 
testify about a specific time when mrs moore poisoned reid 
the issue in this case is to identify the person who is 
responsible tamer said that question is the one on which this 
case turns just because they had elevated arsenic levels does not 
identify her as the perpetrator 
