<TEXT>
the supreme court today turned away a 
wisconsin controversy over how much money associations may spend in 
communicating with their members about political matters 
the justices without comment left intact rulings that the 
dispute is not yet ready for intervention by the courts 
the wisconsin education association council weac a voluntary 
organization of teachers and other public school employees had 
urged the court to rule that a state law limiting campaign spending 
cannot be applied to an associations messages to its members 
the appeal acted on today said applying the campaignspending 
limits to such communications would violate freespeech and 
associational rights 
weac announced in the spring of 1988 that it intended to hire 
about 20 of its members to work toward mobilizing the associations 
membership in support of those candidates whom weac planned to 
endorse in the november elections 
after learning of weacs intention members of the state 
elections board expressed concern that certain activities if 
undertaken at the request or suggestion of a candidate might 
constitute contributions to that candidate 
wisconsin law imposes limits on individual campaign 
contributions of 1000 per state senate race and 500 per state 
assembly race 
the elections board met with weacs legislative director in july 
1988 and in august sent the association a letter stating the board 
planned no formal action because there was no evidence that weac 
had violated any campaign law 
weac sued the elections board in state court that september 
seeking a ruling that any expenses incurred in political 
communications with its members were exempt from the spending 
limits even those incurred as a result of contact with an 
endorsed candidate or that candidates campaign committee 
state courts including the wisconsin supreme court last june 
refused to rule on weacs constitutional claims the state courts 
said the claim was premature because the elections board had taken 
no action 
to resolve weacs constitutional claims would require the 
court to speculate both on the nature of weacs conduct and on the 
enforcement posture of the board with respect to that conduct 
the state court said 
in a dissenting opinion from the june ruling justice william 
bablitch said such associational expenditures need not be 
reported and are not contributions within the meaning of the 
wisconsin law 
bablitch chastised his court for leaving weac leaders in an 
untenable position in which they could forego political 
activity which they believe is constitutionally protected or 
proceed with their plans at their peril 
the case is wisconsin education association council vs 
wisconsin state elections board 90492 
