<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to decide in a 
case from california whether employers sometimes must submit a 
unions grievance to arbitration even though the complaint centers 
on a sinceexpired contract 
the justices said they will review rulings that if upheld 
would force litton financial printing division a subsidiary of 
litton industries inc to submit a 1980 dispute to arbitration 
litton prints blank checks at six plants where employees are 
represented by the printing specialties district council no 2 
in november 1980 litton decided to close down the coldtype 
printing operation at its santa clara calif plant and expand its 
hottype operation there 
the move sparked the laying off of 10 employees who had worked 
in the coldtype operation the employees were not laid off on the 
basis of plantwide seniority 
the collective bargaining agreement with the printers union had 
expired in october 1979 about 11 months before the layoff dispute 
arose litton was refusing to recognize or bargain with the union 
the expired contract contained a grievancearbitration procedure 
for resolving such disputes and the union filed grievances for 
each of the 10 laidoff employees 
litton noting that the contract had expired refused to process 
the grievances 
the union then filed unfair labor practice complaints with the 
national labor relations board and the board ruled that litton had 
violated federal labor law 
the 9th us circuit court of appeals upheld the boards ruling 
last january 
the board reasonably concluded that the layoff was a mandatory 
subject of bargaining and that litton therefore violated the 
national labor relations act by refusing to bargain about the 
layoff decision the appeals court said 
in the appeal acted on today lawyers for litton argued that 
just as the employer had no obligation to bargain over shutting 
down the coldtype printing operations in santa clara it had no 
obligation to bargain over the resulting layoffs 
there is no obligation to arbitrate seniority grievances 
based upon facts which occur long after contract expiration the 
appeal said 
justice department lawyers had urged the court to reject the 
appeal 
the case is litton financial printing division vs nlrb 90285 
</TEXT>
