that the threejudge panel improperly exceeded its authority 
the governments response could take months 
the threejudge court by a 21 vote in may ruled that state 
officials must get its approval before making changes affecting 
majorityvote requirements in the states general elections 
the lower court also said any plan to reapportion state 
legislative districts based on the 1990 census must be delayed for 
60 days after a plans adoption by a state apportionment board 
the delay will allow time for any voting rights challenge to the 
new districts the threejudge court said 
the lower court invoked a socalled preclearance provision of 
the federal voting rights act giving federal courts power in some 
cases to review election changes in southern states 
the preclearance authority is based on a finding that blacks 
were victims of deliberate voting rights abuses in the past the 
threejudge court said not merely that past practices 
unintentionally diluted black voting strength 
the panel cited four such abuses in which the arkansas 
legislature hampered the ability of black candidates to win local 
offices black candidates who amassed pluralities in earlier 
elections lost after laws were changed to require majority 
victories in a runoff 
devotion to majority rule for local offices lay dormant as 
long as the plurality system produced white officeholders the 
threejudge court said but whenever black candidates used this 
system sucessfully the response was swift and certain laws 
were passed to close off this avenue of black political 
victory 
the threejudge court said it credited testimony by gov bill 
clinton that the pace of political reform in arkansas is 
quickening and that the rights of blacks are being protected but 
the lower court said the states past record still warrants 
intervention by the federal courts 
the supreme court has asked the bush administration for its 
views in a related arkansas case in which black voters in a rural 
county challenged a majorityvote requirement for party primaries 
and countywide general elections lower courts have upheld the 
system 
the case acted on today is clinton vs jeffers 90394 
