<TEXT>
a report financed by the american bankers 
association said tuesday the cooperatively owned farm credit system 
fueled a land boom in the 1970s that ultimately led to hard times 
in the 1980s 
the report said a 1971 law liberalizing collateral requirements 
for farm real estate loans made by the system unleashed a boom in 
land prices in rural america that saw the inflationadjusted value 
of farmland nearly double from 1971 to 1980 
but the report added this land boom was unsustainable and 
the bubble burst in 1980 by 1986 six years later the average 
real value of farmland had dropped back almost to its 1971 level 
the 1971 law raised the systems collateral limit to 85 percent 
of the market value of farmland from the previous standard of 65 
percent of its agricultural incomeproducing value 
the report the farm credit system reckless lender to rural 
america was prepared for the american bankers association by ely 
amp company inc an alexandria va financial consulting firm 
ron erickson a spokesman for the farm credit administration 
which oversees the system said he had not seen the report 
but erickson said it has been widely known and talked about for 
years that during the 70s when commodity prices were good and 
land values were inflating farmers were eager to expand and were 
borrowing heavily to do so they were basing that and so were the 
lenders on inflated land values 
erickson added in a telephone interview from his office in 
mclean va that the boost in the lending limit allowed by the 
1971 law was an important signal 
in fact he said the previous lending limit of 65 percent of 
farmlands agricultural value was usually around 50 percent of 
the lands market value thus the increase to 85 percent of market 
value was in effect even greater in many cases 
bert ely president of the consulting firm said tuesday in 
remarks prepared for a conference in denver colo sponsored by 
the bankers that the farm credit system unwisely used its new 
powers in the 1970s to overlend to american farmers 
ely said the ensuing financial crunch on farmers will ultimately 
cost taxpayers about 100 billion 
as a result of the damage caused by fcs overlending federal 
government payments to farmers in the 198289 period exceeded the 
earlier eightyear period by 75 billion measured in 1990 
dollars he said 
future government payments to farmers plus losses suffered by 
the farmers home administration account for the balance of this 
100 billion fiasco ely added 
the farm credit system which includes federal land bank 
associations and other lending entities is traditionally subject 
to federal government oversight but it ran into huge financial 
difficulties in the early 1980s with congress in 1987 passing a 
package of reforms and financial bailout 
ely said the 1987 reforms however did not roll back the 
collateral liberalization of the 1971 law 
therefore he said the fcs still has the power to 
overlend again to american farmers and to spark yet another 
farmland boom and bust 
