a wave of opposition arose today to a proposal 
before us roman catholic bishops that would allow lay people to 
conduct funeral services when clergy arent available 
a succession of disapproving speeches at a meeting of the 
national conference of catholic bishops left the plan in doubt 
bishop elden f curtiss of helena mont said such a step would 
send a wrong signal that the church is moving from an 
ordained to a nonordained ministry 
the time when people most want a priest is when they are 
dying at death and afterward he said 
results of a ballot vote on the measure were to be disclosed in 
late afternoon 
while a big proportion of the floor debate consisted of 
criticism of the proposal several bishops strongly supported it 
archbishop francis t hurley of anchorage alaska where 
extreme distances and extreme weather accent the need for 
lay people conducting funeral rites said 
it would be corporately narrowminded and shortsighted not to 
allow this provision for the pastoral needs of people at one of 
their most poignant moments the time of death 
under present rules ordained ministers are required to preside 
at funeral litugies but a worsening shortage of priests has 
brought requests that the task be opened to lay persons 
of 45 dioceses where there are some sunday services without 
