<TEXT>
the government effort to reunite beirut 
has kindled hope and skepticism about peace prospects in lebanon 
after 15 years of civil war 
optimists contend the new attempt is the first since the war 
started in 1975 to be part of a comprehensive peace accord 
sponsored by the arab league and backed by the un security 
council 
never before has there been such an international consensus to 
resolve the lebanese conflict said christian warlord elie 
hobeika 
the syrian army is dead serious this time to help lebanese 
troops smother any defiance by any militia said hobeika a 
staunch ally of syria 
pessimists argue the two previous bids to unite beirut collapsed 
in renewed warfare despite the presence of the syrian army in 1976 
and an international peacekeeping force in 1984 
we hope it will work this time but frankly what guarantees do 
we really have that history wont repeat itself said a 
commentary broadcast by beiruts voice of the people radio station 
president elias hrawis government has given the eight major 
moslem and christian militias 10 days beginning last saturday to 
evacuate beirut and its suburbs with their weapons 
all militia commands have publicly pledged to meet the monday 
deadline hrawis troops then are scheduled to conduct a 
housetohouse search for weapons that might have been left in 
secret hideouts 
the militia pullout is a key element in the peace plan which 
was brokered by the arab league and approved by the lebanese 
parliament in a session held in the saudi town of taif in september 
1988 
the plan provides for creating a militiafree greater beirut 
as a first step toward restoring government authority over all 
lebanons territory 
it also gives the moslem majority of 55 percent an equal share 
of power with the christians who dominated the government army 
parliament and judiciary since lebanon gained independence from 
france in 1943 
despite the militia pullout hrawi faces the tough task of 
getting the private armies to disarm also sectarian suspicions 
run deep and not all the warlords are happy about the even 
distribution of power 
the 200000strong druse moslems for instance fear the larger 
sects like the 12 millionstrong shiites the shiites insist that 
as the biggest sect in lebanon they should have a share of power 
befitting their numbers rather than be treated the same as other 
sects 
many among the maronite catholics the main christian sect 
deeply resent the syrians and their allies 
the peace accord stalled but it was revitalized when the syrian 
army teamed up with hrawis troops to crush christian gen michel 
aouns mutiny in lebanons christian heartland oct 13 
the syrian army entered lebanon as peace enforcers in july 1976 
at the request of christian leaders who were losing the war to the 
moslems and their palestinian guerrilla allies 
the arab league later mandated syrias intervention stating 
that it had prevented the emergence of a plocontrolled government 
in lebanon that would have provoked israel to attack its northern 
neighbor 
the syrians then dismantled the green line that had split beirut 
into moslem and christian sectors 
all militias were disbanded and there were muchpublicized raids 
on their arms hideouts newspaper pictures showed senior syrian 
officers alongside heaps of confiscated weapons 
beiruts honeymoon lasted 26 months the christians resenting 
the syrians highhandedness in their neighborhoods took up arms 
to drive them out 
when the syrians withdrew from the christian zone in september 
1978 after a 100day war the green line was restored and christian 
and moslem militias were again at each others throats 
new alliances were forged rightwing christians struggling to 
maintain their western ties aligned themselves with israel 
leftleaning moslems and palestinians fighting for an arab 
identity sided with syria 
the israeli army invaded lebanon in june 1982 to rout yasser 
arafats guerrillas from their main middle east power base 
in august that year israelibacked christian militia chieftain 
bashir gemayel was elected president of lebanon only to be killed 
in a bomb blast three weeks later 
his vengeful militiamen infiltrated beiruts sabra and chatilla 
palestinian refugee camps which were surrounded by invading 
israeli troops and massacred hundreds 
outrage over the atrocities prompted the west to dispatch a 
multinational force of us marines french foreign legionnaires 
italian bersaglieri soldiers and british paratroopers to keep peace 
in beirut 
in december 1982 beiruts demarcation line was again dismantled 
by the western peacekeepers and the city was reunited anew 
the 5800strong western force angered the moslems by helping 
the mainly christian lebanese army establish control in their zone 
of the capital 
on april 15 1983 a suicide bomber drove an explosivespacked 
van into the us embassy compound in moslem west beirut and 
detonated it killing more than 60 people including 17 americans 
on oct 23 the same year the us marine base at beirut airport 
and the french legionnaires headquarters in the city were 
simultaneously truckbombed killing 241 american servicemen and 59 
frenchmen 
the attacks were the beginning of proiranian shiite moslem 
terror waves of gunpoint kidnappings followed driving most 
westerners and their embassies out of beiruts moslem sector 
on feb 6 1984 moslem militiamen again took to the streets and 
drove the mainly christian army under former president amin gemayel 
out of the moslem sector 
the multinational force fled ending a 17month unification 
experiment the green line was reestablished until hrawis 
government dismantled it again last month 
i think its more than a prolonged truce but probably not a 
lasting peace this time i dare not be that optimistic said 
gamil kassem a moslem pharmacist 
</TEXT>
