in this city where favorable laws lawyers 
and cooperative doctors can make insurance fraud a popular sport 
douglas collins story is typical to a point 
on jan 20 1984 collins crawled up the steps of his south 
philadelphia home in obvious pain he told his wife he had been 
hurt as he pushed a womans car out of the snow and wooden blocks 
under the tires shot out and hit him 
that part was true doctors treated him for fractures in his 
neck and legs and gave him a neck collar and crutches 
the next day collins left the crutches and collar at home got 
on a bus and at one of the stops threw himself out the door at 
the hospital he laughed as he told his wife he was a good 
actor she later recalled 
he sued the southeastern pennsylvania transportation authority 
which agreed to a 25000 settlement 
then his wife by now estranged called septa with the real 
story 
last month collins was sentenced to 18 months in federal prison 
a kind of poster child for septas fullcourt press against 
fraud 
they think they can make a living this way everyone the 
claimant the doctors the lawyers everyone said eileen katz 
deputy counsel for septa and the culture the fabric and makeup 
of philadelphia supports it 
septa which runs the citys trains buses and trolleys charges 
a base fare of 150 highest in the country 
it paid 47 million in claims in fiscal 1990 or 177 percent of 
the amount collected in fares a percentage well above other 
bigcity rates 
we are if not the worst area one of the worst in the 
country for insurance fraud said james kilcur septas chief 
counsel 
pennsylvania law puts few obstacles in the way of someone who 
wants to make a claim and all claims under 25000 go before an 
arbitration panel within eight months 
its a good system for moving cases but its also a system 
that makes it easy for the people who make claims kilcur said 
we also have a lot of lawyers who do this kind of work here and 
we have a lot of doctors who treat these people and physical 
therapists and psychiatrists 
it gets a life of its own after a while he said everyone 
is making money in the system here and in septas case were an 
easy target 
so septa is fighting back 
earlier this month septa won a state supreme court case 
challenging a state law that limits liability to 250000 per 
person or 1 million per accident 
guess whos stealing part of your fare asks one of the 
billboards erected as part of the agencys antifraud campaign 
started in 1989 it shows a man in a neck brace carrying a sack of 
money file a false claim and you could go to jail says 
another 
the campaign includes radio spots and cards in buses and subway 
cars the ads also run in publications read by doctors and lawyers 
the authority has built an elaborate system to ferret out 
fraud a line has been set up for phone tips computers check for 
repeat claimants and video surveillance is used to see if alleged 
victims are really injured 
septa tells its investigators to look for telltale signs of 
fraud a bus or train crash that makes the news usually means a 
rush of shaky claims unemployed men between 22 and 35 are most 
likely to file false claims 
someone who is vague or wrong on details like the woman who 
had a train going the wrong way is eyed suspiciously in one 
case when a car crashed into a bus with no passengers 11 people 
filed suit claiming injury 
after an accident septa sends its investigators out quickly to 
record the names of the injured a subway crash in april that 
killed four has attracted 278 claims far more than the number of 
people septa says were on board some of the claims were filed 
about five months after the crash 
youd think people would have realized by now if they were on 
the train and were injured kilcur said 
about 40 percent of all claims are closed without payment 
septa says new claims dropped from 13005 in fiscal 1989 to 
10355 in fiscal 1990 eight people have been convicted of fraud in 
the last two years most got fines and probation though a doctor 
who submitted fake medical reports was sentenced to prison 
its pretty early on in the game but the campaign is pretty 
active and we are seeing a noticeable decrease in claims katz 
said 
edward s chacker a lawyer and vice president of the 
philadelphia trial lawyers association insists the vast majority 
of claims are legitimate 
no one wants bad claims lawyers doctors or septa chacker 
said 
chacker and katz said septa and the association are working 
together to fight bad claims septa says it will establish a phone 
line for instance so lawyers can call to see if a client is 
listed by septa as having been on a certain bus or train 
trial lawyers are trying to work it out trying to get rid of 
the trash chacker said 
