<DOCNO> AP901113-0117 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
his colville indian forefathers fished 
this stretch of the columbia river with dip nets and spears 
catching hundreds of salmon a day yet hank cate stood recently at 
the chief joseph dam rod in hand hoping to snag just one 
my wifes starting to think im fishing down at the bridgeport 
tavern its been so long since i came home with a salmoncate 
said 
the bountiful runs of salmon here died out decades ago banging 
their heads against the impassable walls of chief joseph and grand 
coulee dams a century ago 12 million to 16 million salmon a year 
swam up the columbia to spawn today only 28 million make the 
trip 
one of the pacific northwests most prized natural resources has 
been decimated by overfishing habitat destruction pollution and 
most of all a gantlet of hydroelectric dams obstructing the 
salmons passage and flooding their spawning streams 
now despite one of the biggest wildlife restoration projects in 
us history conservationists say some runs of columbia river 
salmon face extinction theyre pushing for action under the 
federal endangered species act 
once again the battle lines are drawn in the pacific northwest 
between economics and the environment 
the columbia river is an example of technology gone mad 
said bill bakke executive director of oregon trout a conservation 
group weve squeezed benefits out of the river with technology 
and now were trying to fix the problems with technology its not 
working 
oregon trout and other conservation groups heated up the salmon 
debate earlier this year by proposing that four wild runs or 
subpopulations of columbia basin salmon be listed under the 
endangered species act 
federal wildlife officials wont decide on the listing until 
next spring but the proposal already has ignited tempers among 
competing river users who include dam operators farmers on 
irrigated land and commercial tribal and sport fishermen 
to some in the northwest the salmon issue looks all too 
familiar the region already faces enormous social costs in 
protecting the northern spotted owl a forestdwelling bird whose 
recent threatened listing by federal officials has devastated 
some timberdependent towns 
the salmon issue has a greater potential to impact far more 
people right in their pocketbooks than the spotted owl said rich 
brown an aide to rep ron wyden dore 
wydens office has estimated that if hydropower production is 
cut to save salmon northwest electricity rates could rise by up to 
33 percent 
the technological attempts to save the salmon began in 1980 
federal agencies and dam operators have spent more than 1 billion 
to pump up populations with hatcheries barge tiny salmon 
downstream around dams even shoot off fireworks to scare predatory 
sea gulls away from dams 
but after 10 years conservationists claim the costly effort has 
accomplished little whats worse they say a flood of 
hatcherybred fish actually is pushing wild salmon closer to 
extinction 
there are six species of pacific salmon in the texassized 
columbia basin and hundreds of distinct runs or stream 
populations a listing would apply only to a few of the most 
endangered runs but protective action might be necessary from 
hatching areas 700 miles inland all the way to the pacific ocean 
where salmon mature before returning upstream to spawn 
environmentalists say protecting a few runs would benefit other 
columbia basin salmon and bakke says applying the endangered 
species act would force a philosophical change among river 
managers instead of taming the salmon make the river more wild 
on the columbia river thats an unconventional idea 
the 1200mile columbia is the secondlargest us river by 
volume and one of the worlds most domesticated rivers over 60 
years its onceraging waters have been turned into a chain of 
stillwater lakes its flow is regulated on the main stem and its 
tributaries by 56 hydroelectric dams which produce cheap 
electricity and irrigated farmland vital to the northwest economy 
the grand coulee dam in eastern washington the nations largest 
hydro dam blocked 1100 miles of spawning habitat upstream when it 
was completed in 1941 the dam has no fish ladder a stairstepping 
channel that allows fish upstream fourteen years later chief 
joseph dam was built 50 miles downstream again with no ladder 
chief joseph is 545 miles upstream from the pacific 
most other columbia basin dams do have fish ladders but even 
those dams kill fish 
spring torrents that once swept young salmon downstream now 
stall out in reservoirs the salmon known as smolts must race to 
the ocean against their own biological clock which in 30 days 
turns them into saltwater fish some dont make it and die in the 
river 
an additional 10 percent to 15 percent of smolts die each time 
they pass through or over a high dam some are chewed up in the 
turbines some emerge so dazed they are easy prey for gulls and 
squawfish 
other manmade hazards await at every turn sediments from 
logging roads can turn the porous gravel of streambottom egg beds 
into suffocating concrete salmon swim into unscreened irrigation 
ditches only to die amid the alfalfa 
it makes you wonder how they do it said greg hovland a 
fish and wildlife specialist who tags salmon and traces their 
migration for the grant county public utility district 
the ambitious salmon recovery plan is coordinated by the 
northwest power planning council created by congress in 1980 
under the councils direction dam operators spend about 100 
million a year for salmon about 36 for each returning fish in 
the annual run 
the plans most successful program also is the most hotly 
debated starting fish in hatcheries then releasing them into 
streams as young salmon hatchery fish now comprise more than 70 
percent of the columbias adult salmon helping to increase the 
total annual run by 12 percent since 1980 
but those gains may be shortlived oregon trouts bakke said 
hatchery fish can dilute genetic stocks of wild fish compete for 
food and spawning areas and reduce the entire populations ability 
to survive he said 
hatchery supporters acknowledge there are problems but say 
hatcheries are needed to jumpstart depressed salmon populations 
new hatcheries that better match fish to their local environment 
will help they say 
bakke suggests less artificial remedies release more water over 
dams to help smolts swim downstream limit commercial fishing and 
stop destroying spawning habitat 
he says applying the endangered species act would give federal 
wildlife agencies more authority to enforce such measures now 
they often must negotiate compromises with other powerful river 
interests 
some of those interests aware that reserving more water for 
fish would mean higher electricity rates and irrigation costs say 
the salmon already have enough clout 
wed rather avoid a listing mainly because a listing throws a 
lot of extra bureaucracy into it said al wright executive 
director of the pacific northwest utilities conference committee a 
hydropower group 
in october the power planning council started a series of 
salmon summits it invited all interested parties to help 
create a new river management plan 
but even the best intentions cannot dissolve a hard reality the 
mighty columbia no longer has the water the power or the salmon 
for all the hungry mouths that want to take a bite 
well be lucky indeed if over the next 30 or 40 years we can 
double the number of fish said tom trulove a member of the 
power planning council thats about the limit of the available 
habitat well never have 16 million fish again 
 
editors note david foster is the aps northwest regional 
reporter based in seattle 
</TEXT>
