<TEXT>
business and consumer interest rates should 
begin falling soon if private economists are right in forecasting 
that the federal reserve is ready to ease credit conditions 
members of the federal open market committee the central banks 
top policymaking group gathered for a closeddoor meeting today to 
review recent economic developments and chart a course for interest 
rates in coming months 
in light of a widely held view that the country has slipped into 
a recession many economists predicted that fed policymakers will 
vote to push interest rates lower in an effort to lessen the 
severity of any downturn 
this expectation was bolstered by some good news on the 
inflation front the runup in oil prices that followed iraqs aug 
2 invasion of kuwait has so far not become embedded outside the 
energy area weak demand has kept producers of other goods from 
boosting prices 
the combination of a weak economy and moderation on inflation 
including a big drop monday in oil prices should tilt the central 
bank toward easing credit to lessen the severity of the slump 
analysts said 
we cant really argue very much any more about whether the 
country is in a recession but we can still argue about how bad it 
is going to be said david wyss chief financial economist at 
drimcgraw hill i think the fed will work to keep the recession 
from being a severe one 
the fed trimmed the federal funds rate the interest banks 
charge each other for overnight loans from 8 percent to 775 
percent less than two weeks ago as a vote of confidence in the 
congressionally approved deficit package 
many economists were looking for a further reduction in this 
rate to 75 percent this should be enough to prompt banks to cut 
their prime lending rate by onehalf percentage point to 95 
percent they said 
the prime rate what banks charge their best customers has 
been stuck at 10 percent since last january any reduction would be 
seen as a boost to the economy since about onethird of all 
consumer and business loan rates are tied to the prime 
but even if the fed reduces its funds rate this week banks may 
choose to delay lowering the prime until early december in order to 
bolster their sagging profit margins analysts said 
some analysts said the fed could decide this week to reduce its 
discount rate the interest the central bank charges to commercial 
banks 
the discount rate now at 7 percent has not been lowered in 
more than four years such a move would be the most dramatic signal 
the fed could send of its intention to fight an economic slump 
however allen sinai chief economist of the boston co said he 
expected the fed to opt for the more modest 025 percentage point 
reduction in the funds rate because of lingering fears that 
inflation from the middle east turmoil still could get out of hand 
the developing recession looks bad enough to prompt the fed to 
make an additional easing move sinai said but even with 
another modest easing move the fed is taking an inflation risk 
hoping that the oil and energy inflation rate does not creep deeply 
into the underlying inflation rate 
michael evans head of a washington forecasting firm said he 
believed the central bank under the chairmanship of alan greenspan 
was in danger of repeating the mistakes made by the fed following 
the first oil shock of 197374 
evans said the fed under the direction of thenfed chairman 
arthur burns eased too quickly and ended up allowing inflation 
from the oil shock to become embedded in the economy 
i am concerned that the greenspan fed could be setting the 
stage for a severe bout of inflation later on in the decade 
evans said 
other analysts said they believed the inflation risk is worth 
taking in an effort to jumpstart the economy 
with oil prices taking a sharp drop monday many economists said 
that should spell further relief for home buyers in terms of lower 
mortgage rates which tend to follow the price of longterm bonds 
wyss predicted that fixedrate mortgages which stand just above 
10 percent nationally could dip to 95 percent in coming weeks 
 
 
