<TEXT>
the economic crisis in the northeast has 
stayed out of silicon valley so far defying the doomsayers on wall 
street but fears of a recession have clearly arrived 
remembering the hard times in 1985 and 1986 when bloated 
silicon valley companies laid off tens of thousands of workers the 
operative phrase for most firms here these days is tighten up 
companies are avoiding unnecessary trips watching the cost of 
meals trimming inventory and work force lavish christmas parties 
are out 
computer and chip companies in this hightech mecca have been 
bracing for a recession for months although there is still no 
strong evidence that a major downturn in the electronics business 
is imminent 
sales overall are up from a year ago inventories are down and 
there are no big layoffs despite pockets of trouble 
cash is king apple computer inc is sitting pretty on a 1 
billion hoard built up from 800 million a year ago to get 
through future economic bumps 
apple chairman john sculley says the only people who arent 
acknowledging an oncoming recession are government economists he 
and other silicon valley leaders have been preparing for a slowdown 
by cutting manufacturing and sales costs and lowering prices to 
attract buyers 
entering a recession its better to be coming out with more 
aggressively priced items than highend items said apple 
spokesman christopher escher our newest macintoshes are 
positioned well for a tighter economic situation 
although fat work forces are out companies here have been 
avoiding heavy layoffs 
premature layoffs have mostly been a new england phenomenon 
said jerry jordan chief economist at first interstate bancorp in 
los angeles unlike california that area is really in a serious 
recession 
hewlettpackard co slimmed down a bit from 95000 workers to 
92000 so far this year and it continues to cut back by attrition 
it also plans to close four extra days with mandatory vacations 
between christmas and new years day to save operating costs and 
remove days off as a liability on its books 
national semiconductor corp restructured this summer and cut 
jobs from 32000 to 30000 advanced micro devices inc is expected 
to cut about 1200 jobs by years end 
in each of those cases though the cuts are related to the 
distinct business conditions impacting the companies as a whole 
the computer and chip industries here are holding off a major 
downturn 
in the last couple of months theres been a general 
tightening said fred zieber of dataquest inc a hightech 
market research firm in san jose theres a lot of concern among 
management about the nearterm future because they just dont know 
what sort of recession there may or may not be 
its been more of a management control reaction more 
anticipation than reality the numbers by and large dont support 
the concern 
unlike the hard times that have hit the northeast especially 
along the hightech corridor of route 128 in massachusetts the 
computer companies here are not heavily dependent upon military or 
aerospace contracts which have suffered in recent years in 
silicon valley the computer companies focus more on workstations 
personal computers and peripherals 
one sign that things may get worse came earlier this month when 
businessland inc a san josebased retail firm reported a 198 
million loss for its first fiscal quarter and said it would lay off 
780 people or 20 percent of its work force by years end 
david norman businesslands chief executive officer attributed 
the revenue drop to industry pricecutting new product 
introductions and sluggish capital equipment spending by 
corporations 
apples new lowerpriced macintoshes appear to be selling 
briskly and sales are good at hewlettpackard sun microsystems 
inc and other computer companies sun is expected to receive a 
boost from the sparcstation 2 line recently introduced the 
graphics workstations which range in price from 14995 to 
49995 are far more powerful and versatile than the bestselling 
sparcstation 1 
computer chip orders rose modestly through the summer 
increasing 98 percent in september alone over a year ago theyre 
expected to keep increasing into next year 
the statistics at this point do not indicate a recession in 
the semiconductor industry said tom beermann spokesman for the 
trade group semiconductor industry association 
a recent sia forecast estimated worldwide chip sales would grow 
125 percent in 1991 following a year of relatively flat growth 
from 1989s 488 billion to about 495 billion this year if war 
breaks out in the middle east the group estimated chip sales would 
grow by a more moderate 625 percent next year 
but those rosy numbers mask a severe drop in sales of memory 
chips which are down 18 percent this year according to dataquest 
the drop there is mostly hurting the japanese manufacturers who 
dominate the memory market 
silicon valley chipmakers who specialize in more advanced 
devices are benefiting from a 12 percent rise in microprocessor 
sales 7 percent in logic chips and 7 percent in analog chips 
the chip and computer industries may be just fine overall but 
that doesnt mean there isnt a lot of pain in a lot of 
companies said dataquests zieber i think youll have a tough 
market for awhile but not one that completely falls apart if 
theres a debacle coming its not real evident so far 
inventories of semiconductors are relatively flat and 
inventories of computers are up only slightly zieber said 
by historical standards theyre both a little below average 
which is good he said if you get too much inventory then you 
have to cut back twice as far if a recession sets in 
even companies that are flush such as intel corp maker of the 
popular chips that act as the brains of international business 
machine corps personal computers and ibm clones are yielding 
to the economic uncertainties 
were looking at critical hires only said pam pollace an 
intel spokeswoman were seeking to be conscientious about 
internal controls inventory spending were asking people to 
avoid unnecessary travel and expenses 
intels earnings remain strong rising to 172 million in the 
third quarter from 72 million a year ago 
intel is boosting spending for research and development from 
422 million last year to 600 million this year pollace said 
because in this business you need to continue that to keep moving 
ahead with the technology 
advanced micro devices lost 237 million in the last two 
quarters and expects to post another loss in the current quarter 
but the company is cautious about laying off workers because it 
believes its longterm prospects are solid 
the company recently completed a 200 million development center 
and this past week introduced a microprocessor to compete against 
intels hotselling 80386 microprocessor 
weve been doing things to react to our own business 
conditions which has had the same effect on us as a recession 
said amd spokesman john greenagel amd has not performed as well 
as the semiconductor industry as a whole for some time the actions 
weve taken wed have to take regardless of the economic 
conditions 
