monday the deal is expected to close during the first quarter of 
1991 subject to approval by regulators and other conditions 
no antitrust or other difficulties were expected to interfere 
with the purchase ms shanley said 
the deal follows a consolidation trend among title insurers who 
check property records and guarantee to buyers and lenders that a 
seller of property actually owns it 
ticor once the largest title insurer has lost money recently 
as has the 4 billion industry in general price squeezing claims 
inflation and sagging real estate markets have contributed to the 
problems 
a previous agreement to buy ticor by general motor corps data 
processing unit fell apart last month reportedly because ticors 
problems were worse than anticipated 
ticor is privately owned and doesnt disclose profit and loss 
figures but ms shanley acknowledged it lost money in 1989 
the same would be the case in 1990 especially with the real 
estate situation the way it is she said 
the title insurance industry reported losses on operations of 
112 million in 1988 and 154 million in 1989 although investment 
income cushioned the losses according to the american land title 
association 
