<TEXT>
the government said tuesday it wants to introduce 
more competition into britains multibilliondollar 
telecommunications market and end the control held by giant british 
telecom 
british telecommunications plc which the government privatized 
six years ago controls about 97 percent of the local telephone 
market the rest is held by mercury communications ltd 
trade secretary peter lilley outlined to the house of commons 
the governments proposal for allowing new players into the local 
domestic long distance and international markets 
foreign companies would be allowed to apply for licenses in all 
three telecommunications categories the trade department said 
the new competitors progressively would be allowed equal access 
to british telecoms existing british infrastructure lilley said 
lilley also said government price constraints on british telecom 
should remain in place until 1993 under the constraints set by the 
office of telecommunications the company can raise no more than 
45 percent below the rate of inflation which is 109 percent 
this country has already benefited from our policies of 
privatization and competition and because of the uks lead we are 
becoming a telecommunications hub for western europe lilley 
said 
the government is committed to reinforce this lead and to 
ensure that consumers have the widest possible services at the most 
competitive price he said 
british telecom said it welcomed the governments general 
thrust for greater competition and choice but it was 
disappointed that cable television companies would be allowed to 
continue their monopoly in providing entertainment services 
lilley said british telecom would be barred from that market for 
the next 10 years 
british telecom has 19 million residential and 6 million 
business customers it had aftertax profit of 154 billion pounds 
or 3 billion in its last fiscal year on revenue of 123 billion 
pounds 24 billion 
the government invited comment on its plan until jan 14 
